		<br>
		</td></tr></table>
	<!-- Postbit User Info -->
</td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 12-11-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">08:38 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>The post you reference is my post.  The point you make is simply contraindicated by reality.  Cheater motivation in Half-life was usually motivated by one of two things.  Desire for fun, or desire for apparent skill.  Cheating in EQ is motivated by those two things AND the desire for money.</b></td></tr></table><br />
<br />
I grant you this, with prejudice, read below.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>I submit that if SOE did as only as much as Valve or Blizzard to stop hacks or cheats, then you'd have rampant cheating in EQ.  As it is, it's *hard* to cheat in EQ.  And because it is hard, the you need more motivation to go out and do it.  While I won't compare the relative situation of fun and desire, the addition of making money in the game is unlikely to *slow* the use of cheats and hacks.</b></td></tr></table><br />
<br />
Half-Life and its counterparts are patched regularly to avoid player hacks. This is to maintain a reputation among the community. Without a solid reputation, sales for Half-Life 2 (or its counterparts) are apt to suffer. Regardless, without any hard data, neither one of us has a solid foundation here. Because EverQuest has the added impetus of economic gain, I grant you this argument, with prejudice, read below.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>Furthermore, you argue, once again, that if people making $$$ didn't do it, someone else would.  This is a morally flawed argument.  If you shoot your wife, and then tell the courts that if you hadn't shot her, her father would have that night, then you're still guilty.  If you steal a pack of gum, and tell the courts that another kid was about to steal that pack of gum, you're still guilty.</b></td></tr></table><br />
<br />
As an absolute moralist, this was the furthest from my intention in arguing. Hacking and cheating *are* wrong, I was only trying to observe that the buying and selling of platinum was not solidly linked to encouraging them.  In addition, I was arguing that because of the very fact that the American dollar and platinum have an exchange rate, platinum has an intrinsic value to certain people that would encourage hacking to the same extent that taking the American dollar out of the equation would.  Herego, the encouragement of cheating is related not to the American dollar, but rather to platinum itself, and the link is broken.<br />
<br />
Furthermore, and again as an absolute moralist, you have yet to show that buying and selling platinum is a morally wrong action in and of itself.  Because the purchase of platinum encourages cheating does not make the purchase inherently wrong.  Likewise, pushing someone down a set of stairs does not imply that stairs are morally wrong.  Knifing someone does not imply that knives are wrong.  Shooting someone does not imply that guns are wrong.  The fact that people abuse heroine does not make heroine wrong.  Until you prove that person A selling person B some amount of platinum is wrong, the fact that it encourages cheating, while practically significant, is morally irrelevant. However, continue reading, I have more to say on this at the end.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>If you give a friend 5k, because you like him, or you have no use for the 5k, that's one thing.  However, when you sell 50k to Yantis, for $45 to fix your dishwasher, or feed your starving somalian children, or whatever, you are giving it to him because what he gives you back is worth more in return.  Therefore, it creates a reason for you to generate more money than you need for the game, or all your friends, or even everyone you've ever grouped with.  Because while you'd get sick and tired of farming a 250kpp item if all you were gonna do is give out 5k to every newbie in Gfaydark, you will not stop doing the same farming, exploit, cheat, hack, or even simple honest money making if that 250kpp is going to be half your rent check for the month.</b></td></tr></table><br />
<br />
Again, the fact that buying and selling platinum encourages people to play the game does not make it morally wrong. See above arguments, I believe they all hold here.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>Selling platinum makes platinum valuable much higher quantities than the game mechanics do.  Thus, more platinum is introduced into the economy.<br />
<br />
2) Selling platinum reintroduces coin into the economy, which is a good thing.<br />
<br />
This is a *very* complicated economic principal, which I am not fully equipped to address.  But I can say one thing to this statement.  <br />
<br />
While it is not inherently false, it is likely, that on the majority of EQ servers, the economy is one of consistent deflation.  Consistently deflated economies DO NOT need more currency.  <br />
<br />
They need less.  Less of something is more valuable.  The less valuable platinum becomes, the more out of reach items traded between players become to those who are not already rich, and are not participating in the illegal or unethical methods of platinum gathering.</b></td></tr></table><br />
<br />
This is true. I stand corrected. More platinum introduced into an economy will drive prices up, and since "wages" at the bottom level are fixed (monster coin drops and platinum loot) this will drive items out of range of the bottom most players. However, I would argue that this is a problem with SOE not balancing the NPC-&gt;PC, PC-&gt;NPC economy, rather than "rich" players reintroducing honest money back into the market. It is not the responsibility of rich players to hoard their money to protect the economy.  And yes, I grant that this is also a problem of hackers and exploiters accelerating the rate of NPC-&gt;PC income.  However, see above argument on the morality of buying and selling platinum.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>Exchange of time arguments are fallacious from their outset.  Imagine this:  I work for an engineering company.  While I work for this engineering company, I specifically sign a document that says any innovation I make that is patentable becomes their intellectual property, as long as it is relevant to their business.   I spend time at home sitting and thinking up an innovation, and then go sell it to a competitor or an outside party, without their consent.  They sue me, and I defend myself by saying Hah!  I didn't sell their innovation.  I sold the time I invested in making that innovation!</b></td></tr></table><br />
<br />
The company you work for does own your time. It pays for it.  If SOE was providing you with an office, and a computer, and an internet connection, and a salary, and you used all of these during off-hours to make platinum for personal gain, this argument might be more valid.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>The argument may be a legal loophole, but legal loopholes have very little to do with definitions of right and wrong.</b></td></tr></table><br />
<br />
But then, neither does a EULA. Legal loopholes are not explicity wrong, morally. In this case, the EULA attempts to be overassertive and own the time of paying customers.  Of course, it cannot actually do this and so goes just to the bounds of its legal and moral rights.  The loophole exists because it is beyond SOE's legal and moral grasp.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>But here again, as you make your point, I agree in most ways.  As long as the game is fun, I don't care.</b></td></tr></table><br />
<br />
Phew! I'm glad we agree on something!<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>And it seems to me that you went to great length to defend a practice that you do not care about.</b></td></tr></table><br />
<br />
Guilty as charged.<br />
<br />
As a further irony, I'll now disprove all my own ramblings. The purchase of platinum is, all by itself, cheating (thanks Urry). A player receiving platinum due to influences outside of game rules is unacceptable. It could be equated (for the roleplayers out there) to paying the DM American dollars to have your character happen upon some campaign treasure. If cheating is wrong (and I believe it is) then buying platinum is wrong.<br />
<br />
So I guess I didn't waste my time entirely after all. Although I may have wasted yours. =)<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>But I've spent countless hours enjoying EQ and making friends.  I don't have a horse, I've never touched a flowing thought item, and my best gear is all gifts from my wonderful family guild.  So saying I am a greedy loot-lover is a bit of a low blow. </b></td></tr></table> <br />
<br />
Guilty as charged. It was an unfair generalization, I apologize.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><img src="/forums/images/sig_separator.gif" width="282" height="11" Alt="Hey! Watch where you point that thing!"><br>
<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">

Varyx<br />
65 Dark Cleric
</font></p></p>
