I'm glad we agree plat duping is wrong.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">However if someone legitimately earns their pp and sells it to another person that does not hurt the EQ economy. The money simply changes hands</td></tr></table><br />
<br />
That is not true.  Ascribing real world value to in game platinum gives it a value which causes "legitamate" methods of platinum obtaining to be taxed.  It causes a harmful influx of currency into an economy with no method of letting currency out.<br />
<br />
And, as to someone else, who said...<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">WOW tapped into some strong feelings there didn't he</td></tr></table><br />
Yes.  He did.  I love EQ.  I'm pretty sure a lot of other people here do as well.<br />
<br />
Plus, I like arguing about this.  It combines economics, morality, causality and the finer points of interaction between them.  It's like being in college again!</font></p>
	
