	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 12-12-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">02:54 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">Kialya said in post <a href="http://www.eqcleric.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&postid=#post" target="_blank">#51 </a>:<br />
<b>I am going to add a somewhat interesting side note to all this: my brother works for a police department in a large metropolitan city and one day while discussing his job he said to me 'do you know why there are rediculous laws on the books such as it is illegal to ride a bicycle drunk?' He elaborated that those petty laws were used as an excuse to detain suspicious persons to check for more illegal activity such as drugs, etc.</b></td></tr></table> <br />
<br />
Ok gonna steal the thread for a moment here. First let me say I respect and appreciate what your brother does for a living. However his statement is DEAD wrong. Laws like riding a bicycle while drunk were made because some dumbass rode his bike drunk and either got himself killed or someone else, or has done some extreme damage to public or private property or the potential for such a thing to happen is greatly increased while operating any form of transportation while intoxicated. Example: a few years back a man was riding his horse along the side of a highway while intoxicated, his inability to think clearly caused him to make a decision to ride across the road without looking before he turned. In doing so he caused an accident that sent a family to the hospital and destroyed their vehicle. The man on the horse was charged with DUI and convicted. Sounds crazy I know, however, it can clearly be stated his alcohol consumption was a direct cause of the accident and therefor cannot go unpunished because you or someone else thinks it's ok to operate a horse while drunk in a public place.<br />
<br />
Second point, while there are some whacked up laws out there, most were created because the potential for something greater was there. Laws are created for the protection of the public. NOT to give Law enforcement the right to Harrass the public as your brother wants to imply.<br />
<br />
Now with that said, let me say this, there are some laws I do not agree with nor do I think are fair. However, as an officer of the law, it is not my right to decide what is fair or right but to enforce said laws. And on that point, let me say this also, a Police Officer has the right to exercise something called "Officer Discretion" which is a lose lose situation for a police officer and whole different can of worms. This whole thing is a BIG can of worms that can be argued till we are all blue in the face, but I felt I had to speak up and make clear that your brothers original statement was flawed.</font></p>
	
