	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 12-12-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">04:51 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">poppah said in post <a href="http://www.eqcleric.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&postid=#post" target="_blank">#50 </a>:<br />
<b>How could it? The money was already there. If I didn't buy something with that money someone else <br />
would. And items raised recently due to a dupe. Not pp buying from someone who killed gnolls all day <br />
long.</b> </td></tr></table><br />
<br />
Prices have been going up for three reasons.<br />
1) There is more money being created than spent. This has always been true. There isn't much that can be done about this without nerfing drop rates on mobs.<br />
2) Plat duping. Self-explanatory.<br />
3) Farmers. This is somewhere between the two above. Since the introduction of selling plat, farming EQ currency and items has become about more than just killing giants in Rathe Mountains to save up for a Spirit Tome. Players go out of their way, beyond the extent they did previously, to try to acquire massive amounts of platinum, because it does more for them than simply being rich in Everquest.<br />
<br />
Farming items is perfectly legal, but there is something inherently wrong with paying a team of people to take turns working a group of character in Sebilis to mine the gems from scarabs there. Farming items is strictly about exchange-of-hands. People sending their private teams to Sol Ro Tower to farm Ornate molds, while I find grievous, is really only annoying. Making massive amounts of pp directly from mobs and selling their drops to vendors has been making prices go up perhaps more than the plat duping has. (Only because it has existed for a lot longer, and anyone knows how to farm pp.)<br />
<br />
Every time I see a "how does a cleric make money?" post on these boards, there are two kinds of answers. Get items players can use, mostly tradeskill-based, and farm XX place to make the money from coin and merchant fodder. I can't attack people that do the latter because everyone has done it at some point, but they do it for their own EQ purposes, not for RL money. Saving 20k this way for a Hierophant Cloak is a game goal, something to work for. Saving 20k to pawn off on the black market is not.<br />
<br />
If you want to argue that the farmers are only selling Fungi Tunics and Earth bows that they acquired, then ask where people get the money to pay for them. Either they bought it from whoever the farmer sold their last pp payment to, or they went out of their way to add the pp to the economy themselves killing Hill Giants...which they will do far more than they would have had to due to previous inflation.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><b>the fact that newbies cant obtain high level items anymore? That can't be true because this <br />
is countered by items coming into the economy now. I have played this came since the month it came <br />
out and the items that were &quot;Uber&quot; then don't compare to what newbies run around with now.</b></td></tr></table> <br />
<br />
A SSoY is no longer a "high level" item though. It has become devalued, because it is obsolete. Newbies that have "uber" gear, by today's standards, are twinks.<br />
<br />
Furthermore, players have come to consider newbie-ness to last to a higher level these days, because it is easier to get to 60, with today's items, spells, and other benefits in the game, than it was during Kunark. I could possibly call someone that is level 57 a newbie. (I won't, I think that's wrong, but some players would.) To talk about new players and their needs is to talk about spell drops and items almost on par with the Velious armor that people were oh-so-uber to have before Luclin.<br />
<br />
My ranger is a well-equipped twink. She's level 34, but it would not be unreasonable for a player to have *most* of her equipment by level 55-60, depending on how financially-oriented they were. So let's pretend that she's a level 60 noob. I went to the bazaar yesterday, and there was absolutely nothing I could buy that would be even a minor upgrade for less than 10k. Mind you, I'm not rich enough to afford 10k items on all slots on my twinks. Some of the items I would have once thought about acquiring now cost over 50k. How long would it take a level 60 person, new-to-game, without a lot of resources at their disposal, to earn 50k?<br />
<br />
Depending on their best known method of earning plat, maybe longer than it would take to earn $50 flipping burgers.</font></p>
	
	<p>Only the exceptions can be exceptional.

Friends don't let friends do tradeskills. (tm)</p>
	<p></p>
	</td></tr></table>
