	<!-- Postbit User Info -->
</td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 12-16-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">03:49 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">The fact that people abuse heroine does not make heroine wrong. Until you prove that person A selling person B some amount of platinum is wrong, the fact that it encourages cheating, while practically significant, is morally irrelevant. However, continue reading, I have more to say on this at the end.</td></tr></table><br />
<br />
I read on, and I understand the ultimate conclusion you came to below, but I wanted to address this point.  The fact that it encourages cheating is both practically significant and morally relevant.  If we accept that cheating is an immoral behavior, and we accept that to encourage or facilitate immoral behavior is, itself, immoral, then we must accept that buying platinum, even if it is not, of it's own essence, immoral, it is immoral because of the effect it has.<br />
<br />
To use your own example, saying that People abuse heroin does not make heroin immoral.  However, I propose, and assume that without extensive argument it can be accepted, that the actions of producing, transporting, trafficking and selling heroin are immoral because those practices encourage immoral acts.  <br />
<br />
Causality is a train I prefer not to derail, so if you do not accept that heroin abuse is a direct consequence of heroin production, transporting, trafficking and sales, please just say so.  At some point we have to say that A causes B.  I am willing to accept that without A, there would be no B, so therefore A causes B.<br />
<br />
<i>EDIT: I read this and realized while it touches on one of your examples, it leaves alone the thornier issues of guns and knives.  Furthermore, it reads as if it simply overtakes them.<br />
<br />
Without getting into a discourse on gun control and the morality of weapons, I submit that murder is possible without weapons, where drug abuse is not.  And while shooting is not possible without guns, and stabbing without something sharp, these are implicitly different because of the element of *choice* that is part of their use.  Heroin, and indeed, any addictive drug, contains an innocence followed by a compulsion which is more significant, and easier to assert the immorality of the precedents.<br />
<br />
However, getting back to all of this, it means that I have disproved myself.  PP buying is not implicitly wrong because it does not *necessarily* compel more cheating.  Free choice is equally at work here as it is in the distribution of knives and handguns.<br />
<br />
Jeez.  If anyone else can follow my arguments, please say so.  They're starting to no longer make sense to me.  This is what happens when you type as you think.</i> <br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">As a further irony, I'll now disprove all my own ramblings. The purchase of platinum is, all by itself, cheating (thanks Urry). A player receiving platinum due to influences outside of game rules is unacceptable. It could be equated (for the roleplayers out there) to paying the DM American dollars to have your character happen upon some campaign treasure. If cheating is wrong (and I believe it is) then buying platinum is wrong.</td></tr></table><br />
<br />
Heh, I enjoyed reading your whole post, Varyx.<br />
<br />
The point you make here, at the end, is, to my mind, the crux of the matter, and that's the reason my very first post in this thread had to do with it.  However, I was attempt to do more than simply assert that cheating was wrong and that pp buying = cheating.<br />
<br />
Specifically, I was trying to couch it in terms of an overall moral imperative.  <i>Why</i> is cheating wrong?  It is wrong because cheating, in a competitive environment, necessarily begets more cheating.  <br />
<br />
I believe at this point, Varyx, to proceed any further in our conversations, we'd have to begin to establish such questions as "What is morality?"  <br />
<br />
Is it the violation of an implicit social agreement?  Is it behaving in such a way that retards pleasure and enhances pain?  Is it behaving in a way that, if the categorical imperative is applied, would bring the world to a halt?<br />
<br />
I thank you for a very interesting point and counterpoint.<br />
<br />
I'm glad that at the heart of it, we agree.  And I look forward to another discussion springing up where I can exercise my underutilized philosophy muscles.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><i>Last edited by Moonsorrow on 12-16-2003 at 03:56 PM</i></font></p>
	</td></tr></table>
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	</td>
</tr>
